# Quality Standards

## HTML

- Use semantic elements (`<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<header>`, `<footer>`) -- never generic `<div>` soup
- Every `<img>` requires a meaningful `alt` attribute
- Every form control requires an associated `<label>` (via `for`/`id` or wrapping)
- Every `<button>` must have an accessible name (visible text or `aria-label`)
- Use ARIA attributes only when native semantics are insufficient
- Validate nesting: no `<div>` inside `<p>`, no interactive elements inside other interactive elements

## CSS

- Mobile-first: base styles target small screens (~375px), scale up with `min-width` breakpoints at `600px` and `1024px`
- Use CSS custom properties defined in `style.css` for colors, spacing, and typography -- do not introduce new hardcoded values
- Ensure sufficient color contrast (WCAG AA: 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text)
- Interactive elements must have visible `:focus` styles for keyboard navigation

## JavaScript

- ES module pattern: use `import`/`export`, no implicit globals, no `var`
- Every `async` operation must have `try`/`catch` with user-facing error feedback
- Separate logic from DOM manipulation: pure functions for data processing, thin DOM layer that calls them
- No hardcoded Firestore paths or config values -- use constants or config imports from `js/firebase-config.js`
- Manage focus after dynamic content changes (e.g., move focus to revealed adventure content after animation completes)

## Accessibility (WCAG 2.1 AA)

- All pages must be fully keyboard-navigable (Tab, Shift+Tab, Enter, Escape)
- Dynamic content updates must use `aria-live` regions or focus management so screen readers announce changes
- Touch targets must be at least 44x44px on mobile
- Skip-to-content link on every page

## Testability

- Write small, pure functions that are independently testable -- avoid side effects in logic functions
- Query DOM elements in tests via accessible roles and labels (`getByRole`, `getByLabel`), not CSS class names
- Design modules so Firestore and EmailJS dependencies are injectable/mockable

## Lint Compliance

- All generated code must pass ESLint (`eslint:recommended`) and Prettier without modification
- Use `const` by default, `let` only when reassignment is needed
